# No Inline CSS and JavaScript

## Requirement

All HTML files SHALL NOT contain inline `<style>` tags or inline `<script>` tags. CSS and JavaScript SHALL be external files.

## Inline Style Tags

HTML files SHALL NOT contain inline `<style>` tags:

```html
<!-- FORBIDDEN -->
<style>
  .container { color: red; }
</style>
```

All CSS SHALL be in external stylesheet files and linked using `<link>`:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
```

## Inline Script Tags

HTML files SHALL NOT contain inline `<script>` tags:

```html
<!-- FORBIDDEN -->
<script>
  console.log('Hello');
</script>
```

All JavaScript SHALL be in external script files and linked using `<script src="">`:

```html
<script src="main.js"></script>
```

## Exceptions

Exceptions MAY be granted for:

1. **Critical CSS**: Small amounts of critical CSS that must be inlined for performance (above-the-fold content)
2. **Template-specific code**: CSS or JavaScript that is dynamically generated by template engines and cannot be externalized
3. **Third-party integration**: Code snippets required by third-party services that must be inline

## Exception Process

When an exception is needed:

1. Document the reason for the exception in a comment
2. Keep inline code to the absolute minimum necessary
3. Consider alternatives (e.g., data attributes with external JavaScript)
4. Review exceptions during code review

Example of documented exception:

```html
<!-- Exception: Critical CSS for above-the-fold content to improve First Contentful Paint -->
<style>
  .hero { background: #000; }
</style>
```

## Template Engines

When using template engines:

- Template logic and variables SHALL be in template syntax, not inline JavaScript
- Template-generated CSS/JS SHOULD be externalized when possible
- If template engines generate inline code, document the reason

## Data Attributes

HTML files MAY use data attributes to pass configuration to external JavaScript:

```html
<div data-config='{"key": "value"}'></div>
```

This is acceptable as it does not contain executable code in the HTML.

## Event Handlers

HTML files SHALL NOT use inline event handlers:

```html
<!-- FORBIDDEN -->
<button onclick="doSomething()">Click</button>
```

Event handlers SHALL be attached in external JavaScript files.
